<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-01-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-01-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="493" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d493">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/105</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-01-25"><hi rend="italic">January 25,
                                1921</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received February 17.]</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 279</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In connection with my despatches Nos.
                                247<note n="41" xml:id="d493fn41">Not printed.</note> and 262<note n="42" xml:id="d493fn42"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_535">p. 535</ref>.</note> of December 20, 1920, and
                            January 5, 1921, respectively, I have the honor to enclose herewith copy
                            and translation of a <hi rend="italic">Note Verbale</hi> (No. 4211/13)
                            dated January 22, 1921, just received from the Italian Foreign Office,
                            relative to the sale in China of arms and munitions from Italian
                            sources.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Underwood
                            Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                        <pb facs="0666" n="542" xml:id="pg_542"/>
                        <frus:attachment>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure—Translation]</seg></opener>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Italian Ministry of
                                        Foreign Affairs</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">American
                                        Embassy</gloss></hi></head>
                            <p rend="center"><hi rend="smallcaps">Note Verbale</hi></p>
                            <p>In reply to the Note of the Embassy of the United States dated
                                December 20th last, No. 243,<note n="43" xml:id="d493fn43">Not
                                    printed.</note> the Royal Ministry of Foreign Affairs has the
                                honor to state that if Italian arms were furnished to Chinese
                                buyers, it was done in execution of contracts made prior to May
                                1919, and for which the Italian Government had made explicit
                                reservation in adhering to the agreement signed at Peking the 26th
                                of April, 1919, by the representatives of the Allied and Neutral
                                    Powers.<note n="44" xml:id="d493fn44">See <ref target="frus1919v01#pg_669"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, 1919, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>,
                                        pp. 669</ref>–<ref target="frus1919v01#pg_670">670</ref>.</note></p>
                            <p>In answer to an inquiry newly addressed to the Royal Legation of
                                Italy in Peking, it confirms that no other sale in China of arms or
                                munitions from Italian sources has been made on contracts of a later
                                period.</p>
                            <closer><dateline rendition="#left"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-01-22"><hi rend="italic">January 22,
                                        1921</hi></date>.</dateline></closer>
                        </frus:attachment>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>